 that seek to establish and clarify the stakes, ambiguities, and emergence of philosophical and biological concepts that defined the rise of modern biology. How do transformations in biology and modern medicine shape conceptions of life? How do philosophical concepts feed into biological ideas and experimental practices, and how are they themselves transformed? How does knowledge "undo the experience of life so as to help man remake what life has made without him, in him or outside of him?" Knowledge of Life is Canguilhem's effort to explain how the movements of knowledge and life come to rest upon each other. Published at the dawn of the genetic revolution and still pertinent today, the book tackles the history of cell theory, the conceptual moves toward and away from mechanical understandings of the organism, the persistence of vitalism, and the nature of normality in science and its objects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aGeroulanos, Stefanos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarrati, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyers, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322926040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329197740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291977/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aE